<doc id="325019" wikidata="Q1834342" url="?curid=325019" title="Modular group">
<text>In mathematics, the modular group is the projective special linear group formula_1 of formula_2 matrices with integer coefficients and determinant formula_3, such that the matrices formula_4 and formula_5 are identified. The modular group acts on the upper-half of the complex plane by linear fractional transformations. The name &quot;modular group&quot; comes from the relation to moduli spaces, and not from modular arithmetic.

==Definition==
The modular group is the group of fractional linear transformations of the complex upper half-plane, which have the form

:formula_6

where formula_7 are integers, and formula_8. The group operation is function composition.

This group of transformations is isomorphic to the projective special linear group formula_1, which is the quotient of the 2-dimensional special linear group formula_10 by its center formula_11. In other words, formula_1 consists of all matrices

:formula_13

where formula_7 are integers, formula_8, and pairs of matrices formula_4 and formula_5 are considered to be identical. The group operation is usual matrix multiplication.

Some authors &quot;define&quot; the modular group to be formula_1, and still others define the modular group to be the larger group formula_10. 

Some mathematical relations require the consideration of the group formula_20 of matrices with determinant plus or minus one. (formula_21 is a subgroup of this group.) Similarly, formula_22 is the quotient group formula_23. 

Since all formula_2 matrices with determinant 1 are symplectic matrices, then formula_25, the symplectic group of formula_2 matrices.

=== Finding elements ===
To find an explicit matrix
:formula_27
in formula_21, begin with two coprime integers formula_29, and solve the determinant equation formula_30. 

For example, if formula_31 then the determinant equation reads
